### Software Heritage: everything you always wanted to know and never dared to ask 


## (Roberto Di Cosmo, 60 min)



1. Software source code- an endangered heritage
    1. Forge : Collaborative development => no guarantee (e.g Google Code, Gitorious, CodePlex)
    2. Distribution platform
    3. Archive
2. Software Heritage mission
    4. Reference catalog
    5. Universal archive
    6. Research infrastructure
3. Our principles
    7. Open approach
    8. Objectivity
    9. Long term
4. Different taglines depending on the area
    10. Culture => The Library of Alexandria of source code
    11. Research => building the software pillar of Open Science
    12. Research => The very large telescope of software source code
    13. Industry => the universal software source code knowledge base
5. All the source code (not just public open source code)
    14. Implementation is currently for Online + Open
    15. Chart the source code dimension 
        * Online + open = automation
        * Online + closed = escrow
        * Offline + open = crowdsourcing
        * Offline + closed = Focused search
6. The SofWare Heritage Identifiers (SWHID)
    16. An emerging standard
7. Building together a revolutionary infrastructure
    17. Software graph -> tracks all software around the world
    18. Software blockchain
    19. Open Science pillar
    20. Big code -> data playground 
8. Highlights from the launching phase
9. Supporters and sponsors
10. Roadmap
    21. Launch phase - 2015-2018
        * Vision
        * Team
        * Core infrastructure
        * Identity
        * legitimacy
    22. Building - 2019-2023
        * Expand collection
        * Support use cases
        * Build community
        * Grow mirror network
        * Independent foundation
    23. Flying (2024-infity)
        * Maintain +  Evolve
            * Archive, community
            * Bylaws, organisation
        * Interact + engage
            * 
11. Organisation
    24. The Software heritage Foundation (SHF)
        * Temporarily hosted by Inria foundation
    25. Inria 
        * Day-today operation 
    26. UNESCO
        * A program
12. Outreach
    27. Communication
    28. Policy and awareness
13. Policy highlight: the EU copyright reform
14. Policy highlight: [the Paris call](https://en.unesco.org/foss/paris-call-software-source-code)
15. Policy highlight: open science
    29. FAIR
    30. ARDC (Archive, Reference, Describe, Share)
16.  Collect - Preserve - Share
17. Adoption
18. Community building
19. Evolution in scope
20. Ressources

<table>
  <tr>
   <td>
Question
   </td>
   <td>Answer
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Mohammad: An important component of longevity of a tool (SoftwareHeritage in this case) is its dependencies. Does the core (non-web) component of SoftwareHeritage depend on Python 3.7+? (as I understood from the development pages) If so, won’t this be a problem when Python X.Y comes, that is not compatible with Python 3.7 anymore? For a long-term vision, wouldn’t C (with no/minimal dependencies) have been a better choice? This is how Git is programmed for example: C with no dependencies. Because C is the only language that promises longevity. Also, web interfaces evolve very fast, what is the plan to keep up to date with these changes (won’t such maintenance issues consume too much time+financial resources)? 
   </td>
   <td>We allow and even encourage mirrors to be written in different languages.
<p>
Why python?
<p>
Typically religious issue in programming
<p>
When you choose a programming language is a social issue - who can be the contributors to the project 
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Bostjan: when archiving online software / custom developed web sites, preserving the database schema and content is imperative. Do we expect to support this “form” as well?
   </td>
   <td>“I want to run the software?”
<p>
Nobody was taking care of the code at all, we are building a low level infrastructure only for the source code, not because running is not important, but because we want to focus on the source code.
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>If I want to ask my government to preserve all the code, how should I go about it?
   </td>
   <td>code.etalab.gouv.fr
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>Mirror - how to encourage institutions to have a mirror?
   </td>
   <td>[To complete]
<p>
If you know someone who wants to do massive analysis on source code -you need a mirror.
<p>
ENEA
   </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td>What’s the total size necessary?
   </td>
   <td>Half a peta-byte -> obj storage
<p>
Budget - half a million euros 
   </td>
  </tr>
